1
00:00:04,000 --> 00:00:09,000
那接下來要介紹的是 vocus 的 Mobile Product Leader YC Hsu.

2
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:16,000
他熱衷於為創作者打造令人驚艷且具有影響力的產品

3
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:22,000
那，剛剛提到的，我們這場演講是以英文來進行的哦！

4
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:24,000
讓我們歡迎 YC，謝謝

5
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:37,000
Okay. Hello, everyone.

6
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:42,000
My name is YC, and I'm from vocus, which is 方格子.

7
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:47,000
And I'm very happy to be here as one of the speakers at iPlayground.

8
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:53,000
And a couple months ago, I went to Tokyo for the try!Swift Tokyo Conference.

9
00:00:53,000 --> 00:00:58,000
And I was so inspired by all the sessions and all the people I met there.

10
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:06,000
So after that, I was like, what if I could share our journey of adopting TCA in our production app?

11
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:12,000
And not only for Taiwanese audience, but also for people from other countries.

12
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:17,000
So that's why I'm here. And that's why I choose to give this talk in English.

13
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:22,000
So I hope you guys enjoy my sharing and also enjoy all the great sessions during these two days.

14
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:29,000
Okay. So first of all, let me introduce myself.

15
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:32,000
My name is YC, or you can call me Yi-chin.

16
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:35,000
I'm currently the mobile product lead at vocus.

17
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:40,000
So I'm product manager now, but I'm also an iOS developer.

18
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:44,000
And I've been working with TCA for over one and a half years,

19
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:49,000
including a personal side project called Check-in Box and two production apps.

20
00:01:49,000 --> 00:01:57,000
And I was deeply involved in building the whole foundation of our vocus iOS code base as well.

21
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:00,000
We are building product for creator economy,

22
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:06,000
which is we are helping creators to find their 1,000 true fans on our platform

23
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:10,000
so that the creators can publish their own work,

24
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:16,000
mostly are articles, engage with their fans and monetize their content,

25
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:21,000
which we call it 內容變現 or 知識變現.

26
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:25,000
And actually, we have a website, but we don't have a mobile app yet.

27
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:30,000
So we are going to launch our iOS app in Q4 this year, hopefully.

28
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:36,000
And of course, we are building this app with SwiftUI, TCA, and Tuist,

29
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:39,000
which is a Xcode project management tool.

30
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:43,000
And I will focus more on TCA in today's sharing.

31
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:45,000
So back to my topic today,

32
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:50,000
I'm going to share what we learned from building a production app with TCA.

33
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:54,000
And I would like to start with this simple question.

34
00:02:54,000 --> 00:03:00,000
What is the difference between building a personal app and building a production app?

35
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:03,000
From my perspective, there are three differences.

36
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:06,000
So let me show you.

37
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:09,000
The first difference is the mental model.

38
00:03:09,000 --> 00:03:14,000
So when it's your side project, you are the only one developer, right?

39
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:17,000
So you are the iOS developer, you are the product manager,

40
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:19,000
you are the backend engineer.

41
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:22,000
So you know everything, you can do whatever you want,

42
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:25,000
everything lives in your head.

43
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:30,000
But in a team, every decision has to make sense to someone else.

44
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:33,000
So you are not just writing code anymore.

45
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:36,000
You are writing the shared understanding.

46
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:41,000
And the second difference is the mentalibility.

47
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:43,000
When it's in your personal app,

48
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:47,000
you can hack everything to make it work today.

49
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:50,000
But in production, you have to write code

50
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:54,000
which your team can maintain for years, for long term,

51
00:03:54,000 --> 00:03:57,000
not just something that works right now.

52
00:03:57,000 --> 00:04:02,000
So you are building an app from quick hacks to sustainable code.

53
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:07,000
And the third difference is the feature complexity.

54
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:11,000
In a personal app, features are mostly simple.

55
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:14,000
But in production, everything changes.

56
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:18,000
You have more complicated features like payment,

57
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:21,000
like you have to do the event tracking,

58
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:24,000
which means you have more third-party dependencies

59
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:28,000
like Firebase, Mixpanel, or AppsFlyer, something like that.

60
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:35,000
So you are building an app from simple ideas to real-world complexity.

61
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:43,000
So making architectural decisions is never easy, right?

62
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:47,000
In production, architecture is not just about elegance.

63
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:50,000
It is all about survival.

64
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:53,000
It is about how we manage complexity,

65
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:56,000
how we avoid regressions,

66
00:04:56,000 --> 00:05:00,000
and how we onboard new teammates without fear.

67
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:04,000
And that's why we started to look seriously at TCA.

68
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:07,000
So let me share our experience.

69
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:10,000
Alright, so why we chose TCA?

70
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:13,000
Here are three big reasons.

71
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:16,000
The first reason is the maintainability.

72
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:19,000
Because of the composable modules,

73
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:23,000
features in production apps become messy really fast.

74
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:28,000
But with reducers, we can break the features into small pieces.

75
00:05:28,000 --> 00:05:31,000
And each piece has its own logic.

76
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:34,000
It is reusable, it is testable,

77
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:37,000
and of course, it is composable.

78
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:40,000
So it won't interfere with each other.

79
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:45,000
That means engineers can work on different parts at the same time

80
00:05:45,000 --> 00:05:48,000
without running into conflict.

81
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:52,000
And the second reason,

82
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:55,000
which I think is the most important one,

83
00:05:55,000 --> 00:05:58,000
is having a shared mental model.

84
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:02,000
TCA's core idea is the unidirectional data flow,

85
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:04,000
單一事件流.

86
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:08,000
So that means everyone on the team can see the same picture.

87
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:11,000
So when you look at the code,

88
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:13,000
it is very clear.

89
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:17,000
The view sends an action to the reducer.

90
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:20,000
Then the state changes,

91
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:23,000
and the view updates.

92
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:26,000
Even with some side effects, like API calls,

93
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:30,000
we can still see the result come back as an action

94
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:33,000
into a reducer again.

95
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:36,000
So everything is expected.

96
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:39,000
There is no guessing and no surprises.

97
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:43,000
And the second benefit of shared mental model is that

98
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:47,000
the new member can learn and understand the code base faster.

99
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:50,000
Even code reviews get more easier

100
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:53,000
because we all speak the same language, right?

101
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:56,000
So the discussion focuses more on the problem,

102
00:06:56,000 --> 00:07:00,000
not on trying to understand how the code even works.

103
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:05,000
And the third reason is the testability.

104
00:07:05,000 --> 00:07:08,000
In production, things change all the time.

105
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:10,000
So TCA makes it safer.

106
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:12,000
The side effects are clear,

107
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:15,000
and TCA gives you so many useful testing tools

108
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:18,000
for you to write unit tests.

109
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:21,000
So it makes the app more reliable

110
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:24,000
and save us from surprises later.

111
00:07:24,000 --> 00:07:28,000
But, of course, TCA is not magic.

112
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:31,000
We all knew that there would be a learning curve

113
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:35,000
or some setup cost when you adopt TCA in your app.

114
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:40,000
So for us, every architecture comes with the trade-off.

115
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:44,000
So there's no single right or wrong answer here.

116
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:48,000
You've probably heard about the questions about TCA before,

117
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:51,000
like the learning curve is way too steep,

118
00:07:51,000 --> 00:07:55,000
or there's just too much boilerplate code,

119
00:07:55,000 --> 00:07:59,000
or isn't it just over-engineering for most of the apps?

120
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:02,000
And honestly, they are all fair concerns.

121
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:05,000
And after about, like, five months

122
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:08,000
using TCA in vocus's production app,

123
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:12,000
I think we have some answers to those questions.

124
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:15,000
So, what we actually learn from TCA.

125
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:20,000
The first learning is that the learning curve is steep,

126
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:25,000
but for us, I think it is not as steep as you might think.

127
00:08:25,000 --> 00:08:28,000
And yes, the initial learning cost is really high,

128
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:31,000
because you have to learn what is the reducer,

129
00:08:31,000 --> 00:08:35,000
what is scope, side effect, dependencies.

130
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:38,000
But once you get over that learning phase,

131
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:43,000
it really pays off, because the team can move faster,

132
00:08:43,000 --> 00:08:46,000
and you can refactor in a safer way,

133
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:49,000
and onboarding is more smoother than ever.

134
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:53,000
So for us, that is a trade-off, which is worth making.

135
00:08:55,000 --> 00:08:57,000
And if you want to learn TCA,

136
00:08:57,000 --> 00:09:00,000
it is much more easier than it used to be.

137
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:02,000
Like these days, there are more and more

138
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:05,000
free learning resources available.

139
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:09,000
You don't even need to subscribe to Point-Free to learn TCA.

140
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:11,000
For example, if you are in Taiwan,

141
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:13,000
everyone knows 13 (Ethan Huang),

142
00:09:13,000 --> 00:09:16,000
and he has a fantastic free YouTube series

143
00:09:16,000 --> 00:09:20,000
that works through the whole TCA in a very friendly way.

144
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:24,000
And actually, I realized that

145
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:28,000
for most of the experienced developers like you guys,

146
00:09:28,000 --> 00:09:32,000
it was much easier than picking up a brand new feature

147
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:35,000
from Apple's WWDC videos.

148
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:38,000
And by the way, I think Tuist is much more complicated

149
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:40,000
than learning TCA.

150
00:09:40,000 --> 00:09:42,000
So the learning curve is steep,

151
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:45,000
but not as steep as you might think.

152
00:09:47,000 --> 00:09:50,000
And our second learning is more code at first

153
00:09:50,000 --> 00:09:52,000
and faster progress later.

154
00:09:52,000 --> 00:09:56,000
At first, TCA might look like it needs a lot of code

155
00:09:56,000 --> 00:09:58,000
to get started, which is true,

156
00:09:58,000 --> 00:10:00,000
because you have to define the state,

157
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:03,000
the actions, reducers, the view,

158
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:05,000
and for some people,

159
00:10:05,000 --> 00:10:08,000
that feels like overkill for a simple feature.

160
00:10:09,000 --> 00:10:11,000
But in our team, we built a snippet

161
00:10:11,000 --> 00:10:14,000
that helps us generate everything we need

162
00:10:14,000 --> 00:10:17,000
for a new feature, and just in seconds,

163
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:20,000
including the reducer, the view,

164
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:22,000
the state, and the view action between them.

165
00:10:22,000 --> 00:10:25,000
So when we need to build a new feature,

166
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:27,000
we don't have to start from scratch.

167
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:31,000
We just use the snippet and modify what we need,

168
00:10:31,000 --> 00:10:32,000
and that's it.

169
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:36,000
So more code at first, but faster progress later.

170
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:44,000
And the third learning is the testing happens naturally.

171
00:10:45,000 --> 00:10:47,000
We are not suddenly become more disciplined.

172
00:10:47,000 --> 00:10:50,000
It is just because the testing became easier

173
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:54,000
and more natural, thanks to TCA's testing support.

174
00:10:55,000 --> 00:10:59,000
So with TCA, the test flow is very clear.

175
00:10:59,000 --> 00:11:01,000
The first step is arrange, right?

176
00:11:01,000 --> 00:11:04,000
So in TCA, we set up a test store,

177
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:08,000
and then we send an action to that reducer,

178
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:10,000
which is a test store.

179
00:11:10,000 --> 00:11:13,000
And the third step, we check the state mutation

180
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:16,000
after the action is sent into the reducer.

181
00:11:17,000 --> 00:11:21,000
So this simple pattern lowers the barrier so much.

182
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:25,000
So we're just writing unit tests naturally.

183
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:27,000
And not only for unit tests,

184
00:11:27,000 --> 00:11:31,000
we also use snapshot testing for data translation.

185
00:11:31,000 --> 00:11:33,000
And in the future, we plan to snapshot

186
00:11:33,000 --> 00:11:36,000
the shared UI component as well.

187
00:11:38,000 --> 00:11:42,000
So we tested more just because it was easy,

188
00:11:42,000 --> 00:11:44,000
so it happens naturally.

189
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:49,000
And the fourth learning is Tuist

190
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:51,000
make scaling module effortless.

191
00:11:52,000 --> 00:11:57,000
We currently have like 25 to 30 modules in our code base.

192
00:11:57,000 --> 00:11:58,000
It seems a lot,

193
00:11:58,000 --> 00:12:01,000
but Tuist makes scaling modules very easy.

194
00:12:01,000 --> 00:12:03,000
When we need a new module,

195
00:12:03,000 --> 00:12:05,000
we simply run the Tuist scaffold

196
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:08,000
with our predefined template.

197
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:12,000
This creates a consistent module structure instantly.

198
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:15,000
And then we use the Tuist edit

199
00:12:15,000 --> 00:12:18,000
to configure the dependency and build settings

200
00:12:18,000 --> 00:12:19,000
for that module.

201
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:22,000
And finally, we use Tuist generate

202
00:12:22,000 --> 00:12:25,000
to compose everything we need together

203
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:27,000
into a Xcode project.

204
00:12:28,000 --> 00:12:31,000
And for us, the best thing about Tuist

205
00:12:31,000 --> 00:12:36,000
is how fast it makes when we create a new module.

206
00:12:36,000 --> 00:12:40,000
So in the past, adding a new module was a lot of ceremony.

207
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:42,000
You had to edit the project file.

208
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:46,000
You had to add target and tweak some build settings.

209
00:12:46,000 --> 00:12:48,000
It took a lot of time.

210
00:12:48,000 --> 00:12:49,000
But now with Tuist,

211
00:12:49,000 --> 00:12:53,000
it is literally just one command and the module is ready.

212
00:12:54,000 --> 00:12:57,000
And everything is defined in Swift code, not YAML.

213
00:12:57,000 --> 00:13:00,000
So it is also easy to understand and read.

214
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:04,000
So everyone on the team can understand what's going on.

215
00:13:06,000 --> 00:13:07,000
So like what we said,

216
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:11,000
even we have like 25 modules in our code base,

217
00:13:11,000 --> 00:13:13,000
there are never a burden

218
00:13:13,000 --> 00:13:16,000
because Tuist makes scaling modules effortless.

219
00:13:18,000 --> 00:13:22,000
And our next learning is the composable modules

220
00:13:22,000 --> 00:13:24,000
makes everything really fast.

221
00:13:24,000 --> 00:13:26,000
For example, in our project,

222
00:13:26,000 --> 00:13:28,000
we have like a login module

223
00:13:28,000 --> 00:13:32,000
for sign up, sign in and onboarding process.

224
00:13:32,000 --> 00:13:34,000
And we have a design system module,

225
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:37,000
which is for share UI components

226
00:13:37,000 --> 00:13:39,000
and a content card module

227
00:13:39,000 --> 00:13:44,000
for handling some complex interaction on our article card.

228
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:48,000
So when we need to modify the login flow,

229
00:13:48,000 --> 00:13:51,000
we only have to work inside the login module,

230
00:13:51,000 --> 00:13:53,000
which is really fast.

231
00:13:53,000 --> 00:13:56,000
And let me show you another real world scenario,

232
00:13:58,000 --> 00:14:01,000
which is the design discussion.

233
00:14:01,000 --> 00:14:05,000
And the photo was actually just taken two weeks ago.

234
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:08,000
It was me sitting next to our designer

235
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:11,000
and we are discussing the UI bottom padding

236
00:14:11,000 --> 00:14:13,000
in different devices.

237
00:14:13,000 --> 00:14:14,000
So during the discussion,

238
00:14:14,000 --> 00:14:18,000
the designer and I could literally sitting side by side

239
00:14:18,000 --> 00:14:20,000
and we open the SwiftUI preview

240
00:14:20,000 --> 00:14:23,000
for building only for that module

241
00:14:23,000 --> 00:14:26,000
and fine-tune the design together in real time.

242
00:14:28,000 --> 00:14:30,000
So because the module was isolated,

243
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:33,000
so you don't need to build and run the whole app.

244
00:14:33,000 --> 00:14:36,000
The build and feedback loop was extremely fast.

245
00:14:36,000 --> 00:14:39,000
So making the collaboration much smoother

246
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:41,000
and much more productive.

247
00:14:43,000 --> 00:14:45,000
And not only for faster,

248
00:14:45,000 --> 00:14:49,000
composable module also make previews reliable.

249
00:14:49,000 --> 00:14:52,000
Like what QCL just said before,

250
00:14:52,000 --> 00:14:54,000
if you tried SwiftUI before,

251
00:14:54,000 --> 00:14:56,000
you probably seen something like this.

252
00:14:56,000 --> 00:14:58,000
When you put SwiftUI views

253
00:14:58,000 --> 00:15:01,000
and the external dependencies like Firebase

254
00:15:01,000 --> 00:15:03,000
in the same module,

255
00:15:04,000 --> 00:15:07,000
then your SwiftUI preview may be crashed.

256
00:15:07,000 --> 00:15:10,000
But when you separate the SwiftUI view

257
00:15:10,000 --> 00:15:12,000
from those dependencies,

258
00:15:12,000 --> 00:15:14,000
the preview not only run faster,

259
00:15:14,000 --> 00:15:18,000
but also avoid those crashes entirely.

260
00:15:18,000 --> 00:15:21,000
So it makes the preview not only faster,

261
00:15:21,000 --> 00:15:23,000
but also reliable.

262
00:15:25,000 --> 00:15:27,000
And our last learning is,

263
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:29,000
when we ran into problems,

264
00:15:30,000 --> 00:15:33,000
most of the challenges came from SwiftUI,

265
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:35,000
not from TCA.

266
00:15:35,000 --> 00:15:39,000
So things like the reuse behavior of SwiftUI list

267
00:15:39,000 --> 00:15:41,000
or some rendering performance

268
00:15:41,000 --> 00:15:45,000
in complex views or complex animations.

269
00:15:47,000 --> 00:15:48,000
And to be honest,

270
00:15:48,000 --> 00:15:50,000
it was frustrating at that moment.

271
00:15:50,000 --> 00:15:54,000
But I think it is part of working with SwiftUI today.

272
00:15:54,000 --> 00:15:56,000
So like what we said,

273
00:15:56,000 --> 00:15:59,000
there is no single right answer here.

274
00:15:59,000 --> 00:16:01,000
SwiftUI give us huge wins

275
00:16:01,000 --> 00:16:03,000
in development speed,

276
00:16:03,000 --> 00:16:04,000
the consistency,

277
00:16:04,000 --> 00:16:06,000
and the maintainability.

278
00:16:06,000 --> 00:16:09,000
But when you need pixel perfect performance

279
00:16:09,000 --> 00:16:11,000
on complex interaction,

280
00:16:11,000 --> 00:16:13,000
maybe you have to use the UIKit.

281
00:16:13,000 --> 00:16:15,000
So there are always trade-off

282
00:16:15,000 --> 00:16:18,000
between using SwiftUI or not.

283
00:16:20,000 --> 00:16:22,000
You might ask,

284
00:16:22,000 --> 00:16:24,000
should I use TCA in my project?

285
00:16:25,000 --> 00:16:27,000
So here are some suggestions for you.

286
00:16:28,000 --> 00:16:30,000
The first suggestion is

287
00:16:30,000 --> 00:16:33,000
to make sure TCA is a good fit to your product.

288
00:16:33,000 --> 00:16:35,000
At least for now,

289
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:37,000
TCA really comes alive

290
00:16:37,000 --> 00:16:39,000
when you use it with SwiftUI.

291
00:16:39,000 --> 00:16:43,000
So if your current app is still UIKit heavy,

292
00:16:43,000 --> 00:16:45,000
it might not be the right time yet,

293
00:16:45,000 --> 00:16:47,000
but that is totally okay.

294
00:16:47,000 --> 00:16:49,000
But if you are starting a new project

295
00:16:49,000 --> 00:16:51,000
or a new feature,

296
00:16:51,000 --> 00:16:54,000
or you are already using SwiftUI in your app,

297
00:16:54,000 --> 00:16:56,000
then TCA can be a strong choice

298
00:16:56,000 --> 00:16:58,000
in that environment.

299
00:17:01,000 --> 00:17:03,000
And my second suggestion is

300
00:17:03,000 --> 00:17:05,000
to learn by building something small.

301
00:17:05,000 --> 00:17:07,000
So don't just jump into

302
00:17:07,000 --> 00:17:09,000
and try to rewrite your whole app.

303
00:17:09,000 --> 00:17:12,000
Instead, you can start with a simple side project,

304
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:14,000
maybe even something personal.

305
00:17:14,000 --> 00:17:16,000
It gives you more space and time

306
00:17:16,000 --> 00:17:19,000
to explore what TCA can do for you

307
00:17:19,000 --> 00:17:21,000
and without pressure.

308
00:17:22,000 --> 00:17:24,000
And once you've done something,

309
00:17:24,000 --> 00:17:26,000
you can even share your work with others.

310
00:17:26,000 --> 00:17:28,000
And there's a showcase discussion

311
00:17:28,000 --> 00:17:30,000
on the TCA's official GitHub repo

312
00:17:30,000 --> 00:17:33,000
where people post their works.

313
00:17:33,000 --> 00:17:36,000
So I actually shared my first TCA project there

314
00:17:36,000 --> 00:17:38,000
one and a half years ago,

315
00:17:38,000 --> 00:17:40,000
and it was just a small project,

316
00:17:40,000 --> 00:17:42,000
but it gave me all the foundation

317
00:17:42,000 --> 00:17:44,000
that I need when I move on

318
00:17:44,000 --> 00:17:46,000
to the production app.

319
00:17:47,000 --> 00:17:49,000
And my next suggestion is

320
00:17:49,000 --> 00:17:52,000
to cultivate your own best practice.

321
00:17:52,000 --> 00:17:56,000
So don't just try to copy TCA by the book.

322
00:17:56,000 --> 00:17:58,000
Try it, refine it,

323
00:17:58,000 --> 00:18:01,000
and make it fit to your team and product.

324
00:18:01,000 --> 00:18:03,000
And sometimes the right tool

325
00:18:03,000 --> 00:18:05,000
might not be TCA at all.

326
00:18:05,000 --> 00:18:08,000
Like Point-Free has many useful tools

327
00:18:08,000 --> 00:18:10,000
like the swift-sharing

328
00:18:10,000 --> 00:18:12,000
for sharing state management,

329
00:18:12,000 --> 00:18:15,000
or swift-dependencies for dependency management.

330
00:18:15,000 --> 00:18:18,000
What matters is to find the best practice

331
00:18:18,000 --> 00:18:20,000
that truly fits your team

332
00:18:20,000 --> 00:18:22,000
and your product.

333
00:18:23,000 --> 00:18:26,000
So if you are curious about TCA,

334
00:18:26,000 --> 00:18:28,000
the best way to find out

335
00:18:28,000 --> 00:18:30,000
if TCA works for you or not

336
00:18:30,000 --> 00:18:31,000
is really simple.

337
00:18:31,000 --> 00:18:33,000
To start small and build something

338
00:18:33,000 --> 00:18:36,000
and see what you've learned along the way.

339
00:18:36,000 --> 00:18:39,000
And that's been one of the biggest lessons

340
00:18:39,000 --> 00:18:42,000
from my years working with TCA in my career.

341
00:18:43,000 --> 00:18:45,000
So that's all for my sharing today.

342
00:18:45,000 --> 00:18:46,000
Thanks for listening.

343
00:18:46,000 --> 00:18:49,000
And I'll be happy to hear your story after the talk.

344
00:18:49,000 --> 00:18:51,000
Thank you. Thank you so much.

